ay.com|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Club\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Season\n! colspan=\"3\" |League\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[Women's FA Cup|FA Cup]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |[[FA Women's League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|[[Bristol City W.F.C.|Bristol City]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Bristol City W.F.C. season|2019\u201320]]\n|[[FA Women's Super League|FA WSL]]\n|8||0||0||0||5||1||13||1\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |Total\n!8!!0!!0!!0!!5!!1!!13!!1\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerway|georgia-wilson/630639}}\n* [https://www.bcfc.co.uk/teams/city-women-squad/20-georgia-wilson/ Bristol City profile]\n* {{Twitter|georgia1878}}\n\n{{Bristol City W.F.C. squad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilson, Georgia}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bristol City W.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:2002 births]]\n[[Category:English women's footballers]]\n[[Category:FA Women's Super League players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgia_Wilson_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Syrian cuisine", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2015}}\n[[File:\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0648\u0632 \u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0651\u0645\u0646.jpg|thumb|[[Fatteh]], one of the most typical dishes of [[Damascus]].]]\n[[File:Hapalos Artos (soft bread), a traditional Ancient Roman recipe for a classic fine bread, from Athenaeus' Deipnosophistae (16336232886).jpg|thumb|''Lakhma'', also known as \"Cappadocian\" bread among Greek-speaking communities.]]\n[[File:Syrian meal.jpg|thumb|A Syrian meal, with ''makdus'' at the bottom left corner. Continuing clockwise are Syrian salad, ''hummus'', haloumi and baba ganouj, with pita bread partially visible at the upper right corner.]]\n'''Syrian cuisine''' includes the cooking traditions and practices of [[Syrian Arab Republic|modern Syria]] (as opposed to [[Greater Syria]]), merging the habits of people who settled in [[Syria]] throughout its history.\n\nSyrian cuisine mainly uses [[eggplant]], [[zucchini]], [[garlic]], meat (mostly from [[mutton|lamb and sheep]]), [[sesame seeds]], [[rice]], [[chickpea]]s, [[fava bean]]s, [[lentils]], [[cabbage]], [[cauliflower]], [[vine leaves]], pickled [[turnips]], [[cucumbers]], [[tomato]]es, [[olive oil]], [[lemon juice]], [[Mentha|mint]], [[pistachio]]s, [[honey]] and fruits.\n\nAt the beginning of the 21st century, selections of appetizers known as \"[[meze|mezze]]\" are customarily served along with Arabic bread before the Syrian meal's main course, which is followed by coffee, with [[Dessert|sweet confectioneries]] or fruits at will. Many recipes date from at least the 13th century.<ref>Edd\u00e9, Anne-Marie. (1999). ''La Principaut\u00e9 ayyoubide d'Alep (579/1183 \u2013 658/1260)''.</ref>\n\n==Foods==\n[[File:Muhammara.jpg|thumb|''[[Muhammara]]h''.]]\n[[File:Fattoush.JPG|thumb|''[[Fattoush|Fattush]]''.]]\n[[File:Shanklish.jpg|thumb|''[[Shanklish]]''.]]\n\n===Meze===\n[[Meze]] include:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Hummus]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0645\u0635}})\n|a dip or spread made from cooked, mashed chickpeas, blended with tahini, olive oil, lemon juice, salt and garlic.\n|-\n|''[[hummus bil-lahm]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0645\u0635 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062d\u0645}})\n|hummus with meat on top.\n|-\n|''[[Tabbouleh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062a\u0628\u0648\u0644\u0629}})\n|bulgur, finely chopped parsley, mint, tomato, spring onion, with lemon juice, olive oil and seasonings.\n|-\n|''[[Mutabbal]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u062a\u0628\u0644}})\n|mashed eggplant (aubergine)  blended with tahini, olive oil, salt and garlic.\n|-\n|''[[Babaghanoush]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0627\u0628\u0627 \u063a\u0646\u0648\u062c}})\n|eggplant (aubergine) mashed and mixed with seasonings.\n|-\n|''[[Moussaka]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0633\u0642\u0639\u0629}})\n|grilled eggplant (aubergine) mashed with olive oil, tomato, onion and garlic.\n|-\n|''[[Fasolia bi zeit]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u0627\u0635\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0627 \u0628\u0632\u064a\u062a}})\n|green beans with olive oil, lemon and garlic.\n|-\n|''[[Kibbeh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0629}})\n|in the Middle East\u2013 dishes made of bulghur, chopped meat, and spices.\n|-\n|''[[Kibbe Nayye \u2013 burghul]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0629 \u0646\u064a\u0629}})\n|pounded lamb meat, and spices.\n|-\n|''[[Fattoush]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0648\u0634}})\n|salad made from several garden vegetables and toasted or fried pieces of pita bread.\n|-\n|''[[Falafel]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u0644\u0627\u0641\u0644}})\n|a deep-fried ball or patty made from ground chickpeas, fava beans, or both.\n|-\n|''[[Olives]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0632\u064a\u062a\u0648\u0646}})\n|\n|-\n|''[[Halloumi cheese]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062c\u0628\u0646\u0629 \u062d\u0644\u0648\u0645\u064a}})\n|usually sliced and grilled or fried.\n|-\n|''[[Labneh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0629}})\n|strained yogurt which tastes similar to cream or sour cream only more tart.\n|-\n|''[[Shanklish]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0634\u0646\u0643\u0644\u064a\u0634}})\n|cow's milk or sheep's milk cheeses.\n|-\n|''[[Makdous|Makdus]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0643\u062f\u0648\u0633}})\n|Stuffed and pickled eggplants.\n|-\n|''[[Yalanji]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u064a\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u062c\u064a}})\n|Vine leaves stuffed with rice and a variety of vegetables and served hot or cold.\n|-\n|''[[Muhammara]]h'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u0631\u0629}})\n|A [[Chili pepper|hot pepper]] [[dip (food)|dip]] from [[Aleppo]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6sp2LXkyEvMC&pg=PA53&dq=Muhammara+syria&hl=en&ei=qLUjTaz9GYycOqzYiYsJ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Muhammara%20syria&f=false|title=Garde Manger: The Art and Craft of the Cold Kitchen|author=[[The Culinary Institute of America]]|edition=Hardcover|publisher=Wiley|year=2008|isbn=0-470-05590-1|page=53}}</ref> made from [[Aleppo pepper]].\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Pieces of Arabic bread covered with other ingredients.\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh bi-s-samn]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0645\u0646}})\n|''Fatteh made with beef or sheep tallow.''\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh bi-z-zayt]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0632\u064a\u062a}})\n|''Fatteh'' made with vegetable, corn, or olive oil. \n|-\n|''[[Fatteh al-makdus]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0643\u062f\u0648\u0633}})\n|''Fatteh'' with ''makdus'' and minced meat.\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh dajaj]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u062f\u062c\u0627\u062c}})\n|''Fatteh'' with chicken.\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh bi-l-lahm]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062d\u0645}})\n|''Fatteh'' with meat.\n|-\n|''[[Lahmacun]]'' (\u0644\u062d\u0645 \u0628\u0639\u062c\u064a\u0646)\n|thin piece of dough topped with minced meat and vegetables \n|}\n\n===Vine leaves===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Yabrak]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u064a\u0628\u0631\u0642}})\n|Vine leaves stuffed with rice and minced meat cooked and served hot.\n|-\n|''[[Yalanji]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u064a\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u062c\u064a}})\n|Vine leaves stuffed with rice and a variety of vegetables and served hot or cold.\n|}\n\n===''[[Kebab]]''===\n[[File:Kebab khashkhash.jpg|thumb|''Kebab khashkhash'' from [[Aleppo]].]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Kebab]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628}})\n|Grilled meat.\n|-\n|''Kebab Halabi'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u062d\u0644\u0628\u064a}} meaning \"Aleppine kebab\") \n|''[[Kebab]]'' served with a spicy tomato sauce and [[Aleppo pepper]]. It has about 26 variants,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticlePrintPage.aspx?id=1591518&language=ar|title=\u0643\u0648\u0646\u0627 :: \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0637\u0628\u062e \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0644\u0628\u064a \u064a\u0646\u0641\u0631\u062f \u0628\u062a\u0646\u0648\u0639 \u0627\u0637\u0639\u0645\u062a\u0647 \u0648\u0637\u064a\u0628 \u0646\u0643\u062a\u0647                                                                                                                                                                                                                 11/01/2006|work=kuna.net.kw}}</ref> including:\n*''kebab hindi'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0647\u0646\u062f\u064a}}), made from rolled lamb, with tomato paste, onion, capsicum and pomegranate molasses;\n*''kebab kamayeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0643\u0645\u064a\u0647}}), made from soft meat with truffle pieces, onion and various nuts;\n*''[[Cherry kebab|kebab karaz]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0643\u0631\u0632}}), made from lamb meatballs with cherries and cherry paste, pine nuts, sugar and pomegranate molasses;\n*''kebab khashkhash'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u062e\u0634\u062e\u0627\u0634}}), made from rolled lamb or beef with chili pepper paste, parsley, garlic and pine nuts;\n*''siniyyet kebab'' ({{lang|ar|\u0635\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629 \u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628}}), made from lean minced lamb served on a tray with chili pepper, onion and tomato.\n|}\n\n===''[[Kubbeh]]''===\n[[Image:Kebbeh.JPG|thumb|''[[Kubbeh]]''.]]\n\nA variety of Syrian dishes made from a fried, baked, grilled, cooked, or raw mixture of [[bulghur]] and minced lamb are called \"''[[kubbeh]]''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629}}). ''Kubbeh'' recipes include:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''Kubbeh bi-s-siniyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0635\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629}} meaning \"plate ''kubbeh''\")\n|A plate of baked ''kubbeh''.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh Halab'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u062d\u0644\u0628}})\n|''Kubbeh'' with a rice crust. Although named after Aleppo, this recipe seems to be of Iraqi origin.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh hamid'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u062d\u0627\u0645\u0636}})\n|''Kubbeh'' with lemon juice.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh labaniyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0644\u0628\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Cooked ''kubbeh'' with yogurt.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh 'qras Grilled'' ({{lang|ar|(\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0623\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0635 (\u0645\u0634\u0648\u064a\u0629}})\n|Grilled ''kubbeh''.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh nayyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Raw ''kubbeh''.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh safarjaliyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0633\u0641\u0631\u062c\u0644\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|''Kubbeh'' with quince.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh summa'iyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u0651\u0627\u0642\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|''Kubbeh'' with sumac.\n|}\n\n===''Mahshi''===\n[[Image:Kousa Mahshi.jpg|right|thumb|''[[Kousa mahshi|Kusa mahshi]]''.]]\nA famous dish served in Syria is made from vegetables (usually [[zucchini]]\u2014{{lang|ar|\u0643\u0648\u0633\u0627}} / ''k\u016bs\u0101''\u2014or [[eggplant]]\u2014{{lang|ar|\u0628\u0627\u0630\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0646}} / ''b\u0101dhinj\u0101n'') which are stuffed ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u062d\u0634\u064a}} / ''ma\u1e25sh\u012b'') with ground beef or lamb or mutton, and nuts and rice.\n\n===Street food===\n[[File:Baking bread in Syria.png|thumb|Baking flat bread in the 1910s.]]\n[[File:Syrianstylebreakfast.jpg|thumb|''[[Falafel|Falafil]]'' and ''[[hummus]]'' in a Syrian breakfast.]]\n[[File:Shawarma Sandwich.jpg|thumb|''[[Shawarma]]''.]]\n[[File:Bakdash Icecream (2789962718).jpg|thumb|[[Booza]]]]\nSyrian street food includes:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Booza]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0648\u0638\u0629}})\n|Ice cream known for its elastic texture, which is caused by the presence of [[Mastic (plant resin)|mastic]].\n|-\n|''[[Falafel|Falafil]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u0644\u0627\u0641\u0644}})\n|Fried balls or patties of spiced, mashed chickpeas, most often served in Arabic bread, with pickles, tahina, hummus, sumac, cut vegetable salad and often, ''shatteh'', a hot sauce, the type used depending on the ''falafil'' maker.\n|-\n|''[[Ka'ak]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0639\u0643}})\n|Rings of bread, made from [[farina (food)|farina]] and other ingredients, commonly sprinkled with sesame seeds, occasionally served on the table to accompany [[Syrian cheese]]. A buttery and sweetened version of these, filled with crushed [[Date (fruit)|dates]] or walnuts, is eaten as a dessert, usually served to eat with [[string cheese]] shaped into a [[braided cheese|braid]] (''jibneh mashallaleh'').\n|-\n|''[[Shawarma]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0634\u0627\u0648\u0631\u0645\u0627}})\n|Sliced and marinated meat shaved off a roasting skewer and stuffed into Arabic bread or sometimes [[baguette]], alone with hummus, or with additional trimmings such as fresh onion, French fries, salads and pickles.\n|-\n|''[[Manakish]] ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0642\u064a\u0634\u200e}})\n|Dough topped with [[Thyme|thyme]], cheese or [[Ground meat|ground meat]]. It can be sliced or folded, and it can be served either for breakfast or lunch.\n|}\n\n===Sweets===\n[[File:Syrian apricot paste 01.jpg|thumb|right|Syrians are renowned for producing dried apricot paste (''qamar ad-din'').]]\n[[File:\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0628\u0646.jpg|thumb|''[[Halawet el Jibn|Halawet al-jibn]]''.]]\n[[File:Ataef.jpg|thumb|''[[Qatayef|Qada'ef]]''.]]\n\nSweets include:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Baklava|Ba'lawah]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0629}})\n|Layered pastry filled with nuts, steeped in a honey syrup called \"''<nowiki>'</nowiki>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}), and usually cut in a triangular or diamond shape.\n|-\n|''[[Cr\u00eape]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0628}})\n|a very thin French pastry with butter and sugar.\n|-\n|''[[Rice pudding]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0631\u0632 \u0628\u062d\u0644\u064a\u0628}})\n|made from rice mixed with water or milk and other ingredients such as cinnamon.\n|-\n|''[[Kanafeh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0646\u0627\u0641\u0629}})\n|Shoelace pastry dessert stuffed with sweet white cheese, nuts and syrup.\n|-\n|''[[Basbousa]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0633\u0628\u0648\u0633\u0629}})\n|A sweet cake made of cooked semolina or farina soaked in simple syrup.\n\n|-\n|''[[Halawet el Jibn|Halawet al-jibn]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0628\u0646}})\n|Pastry rolled and stuffed with cheese or thick milk cream, served with a honey syrup called \"''<noinclude>'</noinclude>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}).\n|-\n|''[[Halva|Halweh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0644\u0648\u0629}})\n|A slab of sesame paste studded with fruit and candy/sweets.\n|-\n|''[[Ma'amoul|Ma'mul]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0639\u0645\u0648\u0644}})\n|Biscuits filled with dates, pistachios or walnuts, and shaped in a wooden mould called \"''tabi<noinclude>'</noinclude>''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0637\u0627\u0628\u0639}}). It is a popular sweet on Christian holidays (Easter), Muslim holidays ('Id al-Fitr), and Jewish holidays (Purim).\n|-\n|''[[Taj al-malik]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062a\u0627\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643}} meaning \"king's crown\")\n|Round dry pastry, the centre of which is filled with [[pistachio]]s, cashews or other nuts.\n\n|-\n|''[[Nabulsiyah|Nabulsiyyeh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0646\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|A layer of semi-salty [[Nabulsi cheese]] covered with a semolina dough and drizzled with a honey syrup called \"''<nowiki>'</nowiki>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}).\n|-\n|''[[Qatayef|Qada'ef]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0627\u064a\u0641}})\n|Semolina dough stuffed with a paste made from sweet walnuts or milk cream, with a honey syrup called \"''<nowiki>'</nowiki>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}).\n|-\n|''[[Qamar al-Din]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0645\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646}})\n|[[Dried apricot]] paste.\n|-\n|''Mamuniyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0627\u0645\u0648\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Mixture of [[semolina]] and ghee butter simmered in water with sugar, usually served with salty cheese or milk cream called \"''qishteh''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0634\u0637\u0629}}).\n|-\n|''[[Suwar as-sitt]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0633\u0648\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062a}} meaning \"lady's wristlet\")\n|A disc-shaped pastry steeped in a honey syrup called \"''<nowiki>'</nowiki>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}) while the centre is covered with smashed [[pistachio]]s.\n|-\n|''[[Jalebi|Zilabiyyeh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0632\u0644\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Thin sheets of semolina dough, boiled, rolled and stuffed with pistachios or milk cream called \"''qishteh''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0634\u0637\u0629}}).\n|-\n|''Ghazal al-banat'' ({{lang|ar|\u063a\u0632\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a}})\n|Sugar cotton candy stuffed with pistachios or [[cashew]].\n|-\n|''Halaweh Homsiyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0629 \u062d\u0645\u0635\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|\n|-\n|''Znud as-sitt'' ({{lang|ar|\u0632\u0646\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062a}} meaning \"lady's arms\")\n|[[Phyllo]] pastries with various fillings.\n|}\n\n== Cakes ==\n* [[Nygella Cake]]\n\n==Cheeses==\n{{main|List of Syrian Cheeses}}\n*[[Tresse cheese]] (Jibne Khadra) is a form of string cheese, that originates in Syria, known by its Arabic name '' Jibneh Mshallaleh ''.\n*[[List of Syrian Cheeses#Jibne Baida|White cheese]], a white hard cheese with a pronounced salty taste\n*[[Shanklish]], cow's milk or sheep's milk cheeses\n*[[Halloumi cheese]], a semi-hard, unripened, brined cheese\n\n==Beverages==\n[[File:Arak Al Hayat from Syria.jpg|thumb|Special edition of 5 year-aged Arak al-Hayat (''<nowiki>'</nowiki>ara<nowiki>'</nowiki>'') from [[Homs]], [[Syria]].]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Arak (distilled beverage)|'Ara']]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0639\u0631\u0642}})\n|A distilled alcoholic spirit, transparent in color, made from [[anise]] seeds.\n|-\n|[[Wine]] ({{lang|ar|\u0646\u0628\u064a\u0630}})\n|An alcoholic beverage made from fermented grapes.\n|-\n|[[Beer in Syria|Syrian beer]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0628\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|A beverage prepared from yeast-fermented malt, flavored with [[hops]].\n|-\n|[[Syrian coffee]] ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629}})\n|A beverage made from lightly roasted [[coffee beans]] along with cardamom, and served in small cups (same as the Turkish coffee).\n|-\n|''[[Qamar al-Din]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0645\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646}})\n|A thick apricot juice, typically served for [[Iftar]] during [[Ramadan]].\n|-\n|''[[Mate (beverage)|Al-mateh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u0647}})\n|A [[caffeine]]-infused drink produced from ground [[yerba mate]] leaves and served hot.\n|-\n|''[[Salep]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0633\u062d\u0644\u0628}})\n|A traditional winter beverage which is a flour made from the tubers of the orchid genus Orchis. Salep flour is consumed in beverages and desserts.\n|-\n|''[[Ayran|'Ayran]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0639\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646}})\n|A yogurt-based beverage mixed with salt and water.\n|-\n|''[[Polo (beverage)|Polo]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0648\u0644\u0648}})\n|Mint lemonade.\n|-\n|''[[Jallab]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062c\u0644\u0627\u0628}})\n|A [[fruit syrup]] which can be combined with liquid to form a hot or warm beverage.\n|-\n|''Qahweh bayda<noinclude>'</noinclude>'' ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629 \u0628\u064a\u0636\u0627\u0621}} meaning \"white coffee\")\n|A caffeine-free drink made from water and orange blossom water, sweetened with sugar at will, usually served in lieu of coffee.\n\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[Mediterranean cuisine]]\n* [[Levantine cuisine]]\n* [[Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n* [[Arab cuisine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* Syrian wine [[Ch\u00e2teau Bargylus]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Gerbino|first=Virginia Jerro|title=A taste of Syria|date=2002|publisher=Hippocrene|location=New York|isbn=9780781809467|author2=Kayal, Philip }}\n* {{cite book|last=Kad\u00e9-Badra|first=Dalal|title=Flavours of Aleppo : celebrating Syrian cuisine|date=2013|publisher=Whitecap Books|location=Vancouver, Canada|isbn=9781770501782|author2=Badra, Elie }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline|Cuisine of Syria}}\n{{Mediterranean cuisine}}\n{{Middle East topic |prefix=Cuisine of |title=[[Middle Eastern cuisine]]}}\n{{Asian topic|| cuisine}}\n{{cuisine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Arab cuisine|Syria]]\n[[Category:Levantine cuisine|Syria]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean cuisine|Syria]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern cuisine|Syria]]\n[[Category:Syrian cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2015}}\n[[File:\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0648\u0632 \u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0651\u0645\u0646.jpg|thumb|[[Fatteh]], one of the most typical dishes of [[Damascus]].]]\n[[File:Hapalos Artos (soft bread), a traditional Ancient Roman recipe for a classic fine bread, from Athenaeus' Deipnosophistae (16336232886).jpg|thumb|''Lakhma'', also known as \"Cappadocian\" bread among Greek-speaking communities.]]\n[[File:Syrian meal.jpg|thumb|A Syrian meal, with ''makdus'' at the bottom left corner. Continuing clockwise are Syrian salad, ''hummus'', haloumi and baba ganouj, with pita bread partially visible at the upper right corner.]]\n'''Syrian cuisine''' includes the cooking traditions and practices of [[Syrian Arab Republic|modern Syria]] (as opposed to [[Greater Syria]]), merging the habits of people who settled in [[Syria]] throughout its history.\n\nSyrian cuisine mainly uses [[eggplant]], [[zucchini]], [[garlic]], meat (mostly from [[mutton|lamb and sheep]]), [[sesame seeds]], [[rice]], [[chickpea]]s, [[fava bean]]s, [[lentils]], [[cabbage]], [[cauliflower]], [[vine leaves]], pickled [[turnips]], [[cucumbers]], [[tomato]]es, [[olive oil]], [[lemon juice]], [[Mentha|mint]], [[pistachio]]s, [[honey]] and fruits.\n\nAt the beginning of the 21st century, selections of appetizers known as \"[[meze|mezze]]\" are customarily served along with Arabic bread before the Syrian meal's main course, which is followed by coffee, with [[Dessert|sweet confectioneries]] or fruits at will. Many recipes date from at least the 13th century.<ref>Edd\u00e9, Anne-Marie. (1999). ''La Principaut\u00e9 ayyoubide d'Alep (579/1183 \u2013 658/1260)''.</ref>\n\n==Foods==\n[[File:Muhammara.jpg|thumb|''[[Muhammara]]h''.]]\n[[File:Fattoush.JPG|thumb|''[[Fattoush|Fattush]]''.]]\n[[File:Shanklish.jpg|thumb|''[[Shanklish]]''.]]\n\n===Meze===\n[[Meze]] include:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Hummus]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0645\u0635}})\n|a dip or spread made from cooked, mashed chickpeas, blended with tahini, olive oil, lemon juice, salt and garlic.\n|-\n|''[[hummus bil-lahm]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0645\u0635 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062d\u0645}})\n|hummus with meat on top.\n|-\n|''[[Tabbouleh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062a\u0628\u0648\u0644\u0629}})\n|bulgur, finely chopped parsley, mint, tomato, spring onion, with lemon juice, olive oil and seasonings.\n|-\n|''[[Mutabbal]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u062a\u0628\u0644}})\n|mashed eggplant (aubergine)  blended with tahini, olive oil, salt and garlic.\n|-\n|''[[Babaghanoush]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0627\u0628\u0627 \u063a\u0646\u0648\u062c}})\n|eggplant (aubergine) mashed and mixed with seasonings.\n|-\n|''[[Moussaka]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0633\u0642\u0639\u0629}})\n|grilled eggplant (aubergine) mashed with olive oil, tomato, onion and garlic.\n|-\n|''[[Fasolia bi zeit]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u0627\u0635\u0648\u0644\u064a\u0627 \u0628\u0632\u064a\u062a}})\n|green beans with olive oil, lemon and garlic.\n|-\n|''[[Kibbeh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0629}})\n|in the Middle East\u2013 dishes made of bulghur, chopped meat, and spices.\n|-\n|''[[Kibbe Nayye \u2013 burghul]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0629 \u0646\u064a\u0629}})\n|pounded lamb meat, and spices.\n|-\n|''[[Fattoush]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0648\u0634}})\n|salad made from several garden vegetables and toasted or fried pieces of pita bread.\n|-\n|''[[Falafel]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u0644\u0627\u0641\u0644}})\n|a deep-fried ball or patty made from ground chickpeas, fava beans, or both.\n|-\n|''[[Olives]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0632\u064a\u062a\u0648\u0646}})\n|\n|-\n|''[[Halloumi cheese]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062c\u0628\u0646\u0629 \u062d\u0644\u0648\u0645\u064a}})\n|usually sliced and grilled or fried.\n|-\n|''[[Labneh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0629}})\n|strained yogurt which tastes similar to cream or sour cream only more tart.\n|-\n|''[[Shanklish]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0634\u0646\u0643\u0644\u064a\u0634}})\n|cow's milk or sheep's milk cheeses.\n|-\n|''[[Makdous|Makdus]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0643\u062f\u0648\u0633}})\n|Stuffed and pickled eggplants.\n|-\n|''[[Yalanji]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u064a\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u062c\u064a}})\n|Vine leaves stuffed with rice and a variety of vegetables and served hot or cold.\n|-\n|''[[Muhammara]]h'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u0631\u0629}})\n|A [[Chili pepper|hot pepper]] [[dip (food)|dip]] from [[Aleppo]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6sp2LXkyEvMC&pg=PA53&dq=Muhammara+syria&hl=en&ei=qLUjTaz9GYycOqzYiYsJ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Muhammara%20syria&f=false|title=Garde Manger: The Art and Craft of the Cold Kitchen|author=[[The Culinary Institute of America]]|edition=Hardcover|publisher=Wiley|year=2008|isbn=0-470-05590-1|page=53}}</ref> made from [[Aleppo pepper]].\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Pieces of Arabic bread covered with other ingredients.\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh bi-s-samn]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0645\u0646}})\n|''Fatteh made with beef or sheep tallow.''\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh bi-z-zayt]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0632\u064a\u062a}})\n|''Fatteh'' made with vegetable, corn, or olive oil. \n|-\n|''[[Fatteh al-makdus]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0643\u062f\u0648\u0633}})\n|''Fatteh'' with ''makdus'' and minced meat.\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh dajaj]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u062f\u062c\u0627\u062c}})\n|''Fatteh'' with chicken.\n|-\n|''[[Fatteh bi-l-lahm]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u062a\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0644\u062d\u0645}})\n|''Fatteh'' with meat.\n\n|}\n\n===Vine leaves===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Yabrak]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u064a\u0628\u0631\u0642}})\n|Vine leaves stuffed with rice and minced meat cooked and served hot.\n|-\n|''[[Yalanji]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u064a\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u062c\u064a}})\n|Vine leaves stuffed with rice and a variety of vegetables and served hot or cold.\n|}\n\n===''[[Kebab]]''===\n[[File:Kebab khashkhash.jpg|thumb|''Kebab khashkhash'' from [[Aleppo]].]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Kebab]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628}})\n|Grilled meat.\n|-\n|''Kebab Halabi'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u062d\u0644\u0628\u064a}} meaning \"Aleppine kebab\") \n|''[[Kebab]]'' served with a spicy tomato sauce and [[Aleppo pepper]]. It has about 26 variants,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticlePrintPage.aspx?id=1591518&language=ar|title=\u0643\u0648\u0646\u0627 :: \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0637\u0628\u062e \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0644\u0628\u064a \u064a\u0646\u0641\u0631\u062f \u0628\u062a\u0646\u0648\u0639 \u0627\u0637\u0639\u0645\u062a\u0647 \u0648\u0637\u064a\u0628 \u0646\u0643\u062a\u0647                                                                                                                                                                                                                 11/01/2006|work=kuna.net.kw}}</ref> including:\n*''kebab hindi'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0647\u0646\u062f\u064a}}), made from rolled lamb, with tomato paste, onion, capsicum and pomegranate molasses;\n*''kebab kamayeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0643\u0645\u064a\u0647}}), made from soft meat with truffle pieces, onion and various nuts;\n*''[[Cherry kebab|kebab karaz]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0643\u0631\u0632}}), made from lamb meatballs with cherries and cherry paste, pine nuts, sugar and pomegranate molasses;\n*''kebab khashkhash'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u062e\u0634\u062e\u0627\u0634}}), made from rolled lamb or beef with chili pepper paste, parsley, garlic and pine nuts;\n*''siniyyet kebab'' ({{lang|ar|\u0635\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629 \u0643\u0628\u0627\u0628}}), made from lean minced lamb served on a tray with chili pepper, onion and tomato.\n|}\n\n===''[[Kubbeh]]''===\n[[Image:Kebbeh.JPG|thumb|''[[Kubbeh]]''.]]\n\nA variety of Syrian dishes made from a fried, baked, grilled, cooked, or raw mixture of [[bulghur]] and minced lamb are called \"''[[kubbeh]]''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629}}). ''Kubbeh'' recipes include:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''Kubbeh bi-s-siniyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0635\u064a\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629}} meaning \"plate ''kubbeh''\")\n|A plate of baked ''kubbeh''.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh Halab'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u062d\u0644\u0628}})\n|''Kubbeh'' with a rice crust. Although named after Aleppo, this recipe seems to be of Iraqi origin.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh hamid'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u062d\u0627\u0645\u0636}})\n|''Kubbeh'' with lemon juice.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh labaniyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0644\u0628\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Cooked ''kubbeh'' with yogurt.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh 'qras Grilled'' ({{lang|ar|(\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0623\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0635 (\u0645\u0634\u0648\u064a\u0629}})\n|Grilled ''kubbeh''.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh nayyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Raw ''kubbeh''.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh safarjaliyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0633\u0641\u0631\u062c\u0644\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|''Kubbeh'' with quince.\n|-\n|''Kubbeh summa'iyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0628\u0651\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u0651\u0627\u0642\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|''Kubbeh'' with sumac.\n|}\n\n===''Mahshi''===\n[[Image:Kousa Mahshi.jpg|right|thumb|''[[Kousa mahshi|Kusa mahshi]]''.]]\nA famous dish served in Syria is made from vegetables (usually [[zucchini]]\u2014{{lang|ar|\u0643\u0648\u0633\u0627}} / ''k\u016bs\u0101''\u2014or [[eggplant]]\u2014{{lang|ar|\u0628\u0627\u0630\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0646}} / ''b\u0101dhinj\u0101n'') which are stuffed ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u062d\u0634\u064a}} / ''ma\u1e25sh\u012b'') with ground beef or lamb or mutton, and nuts and rice.\n\n===Street food===\n[[File:Baking bread in Syria.png|thumb|Baking flat bread in the 1910s.]]\n[[File:Syrianstylebreakfast.jpg|thumb|''[[Falafel|Falafil]]'' and ''[[hummus]]'' in a Syrian breakfast.]]\n[[File:Shawarma Sandwich.jpg|thumb|''[[Shawarma]]''.]]\n[[File:Bakdash Icecream (2789962718).jpg|thumb|[[Booza]]]]\nSyrian street food includes:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Booza]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0648\u0638\u0629}})\n|Ice cream known for its elastic texture, which is caused by the presence of [[Mastic (plant resin)|mastic]].\n|-\n|''[[Falafel|Falafil]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0641\u0644\u0627\u0641\u0644}})\n|Fried balls or patties of spiced, mashed chickpeas, most often served in Arabic bread, with pickles, tahina, hummus, sumac, cut vegetable salad and often, ''shatteh'', a hot sauce, the type used depending on the ''falafil'' maker.\n|-\n|''[[Ka'ak]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0639\u0643}})\n|Rings of bread, made from [[farina (food)|farina]] and other ingredients, commonly sprinkled with sesame seeds, occasionally served on the table to accompany [[Syrian cheese]]. A buttery and sweetened version of these, filled with crushed [[Date (fruit)|dates]] or walnuts, is eaten as a dessert, usually served to eat with [[string cheese]] shaped into a [[braided cheese|braid]] (''jibneh mashallaleh'').\n|-\n|''[[Shawarma]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0634\u0627\u0648\u0631\u0645\u0627}})\n|Sliced and marinated meat shaved off a roasting skewer and stuffed into Arabic bread or sometimes [[baguette]], alone with hummus, or with additional trimmings such as fresh onion, French fries, salads and pickles.\n|-\n|''[[Manakish]] ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0642\u064a\u0634\u200e}})\n|Dough topped with [[Thyme|thyme]], cheese or [[Ground meat|ground meat]]. It can be sliced or folded, and it can be served either for breakfast or lunch.\n|}\n\n===Sweets===\n[[File:Syrian apricot paste 01.jpg|thumb|right|Syrians are renowned for producing dried apricot paste (''qamar ad-din'').]]\n[[File:\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0628\u0646.jpg|thumb|''[[Halawet el Jibn|Halawet al-jibn]]''.]]\n[[File:Ataef.jpg|thumb|''[[Qatayef|Qada'ef]]''.]]\n\nSweets include:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Baklava|Ba'lawah]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0629}})\n|Layered pastry filled with nuts, steeped in a honey syrup called \"''<nowiki>'</nowiki>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}), and usually cut in a triangular or diamond shape.\n|-\n|''[[Cr\u00eape]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0628}})\n|a very thin French pastry with butter and sugar.\n|-\n|''[[Rice pudding]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0631\u0632 \u0628\u062d\u0644\u064a\u0628}})\n|made from rice mixed with water or milk and other ingredients such as cinnamon.\n|-\n|''[[Kanafeh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0643\u0646\u0627\u0641\u0629}})\n|Shoelace pastry dessert stuffed with sweet white cheese, nuts and syrup.\n|-\n|''[[Basbousa]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0633\u0628\u0648\u0633\u0629}})\n|A sweet cake made of cooked semolina or farina soaked in simple syrup.\n\n|-\n|''[[Halawet el Jibn|Halawet al-jibn]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0628\u0646}})\n|Pastry rolled and stuffed with cheese or thick milk cream, served with a honey syrup called \"''<noinclude>'</noinclude>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}).\n|-\n|''[[Halva|Halweh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0644\u0648\u0629}})\n|A slab of sesame paste studded with fruit and candy/sweets.\n|-\n|''[[Ma'amoul|Ma'mul]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0639\u0645\u0648\u0644}})\n|Biscuits filled with dates, pistachios or walnuts, and shaped in a wooden mould called \"''tabi<noinclude>'</noinclude>''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0637\u0627\u0628\u0639}}). It is a popular sweet on Christian holidays (Easter), Muslim holidays ('Id al-Fitr), and Jewish holidays (Purim).\n|-\n|''[[Taj al-malik]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062a\u0627\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643}} meaning \"king's crown\")\n|Round dry pastry, the centre of which is filled with [[pistachio]]s, cashews or other nuts.\n\n|-\n|''[[Nabulsiyah|Nabulsiyyeh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0646\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|A layer of semi-salty [[Nabulsi cheese]] covered with a semolina dough and drizzled with a honey syrup called \"''<nowiki>'</nowiki>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}).\n|-\n|''[[Qatayef|Qada'ef]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0627\u064a\u0641}})\n|Semolina dough stuffed with a paste made from sweet walnuts or milk cream, with a honey syrup called \"''<nowiki>'</nowiki>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}).\n|-\n|''[[Qamar al-Din]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0645\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646}})\n|[[Dried apricot]] paste.\n|-\n|''Mamuniyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u0627\u0645\u0648\u0646\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Mixture of [[semolina]] and ghee butter simmered in water with sugar, usually served with salty cheese or milk cream called \"''qishteh''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0634\u0637\u0629}}).\n|-\n|''[[Suwar as-sitt]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0633\u0648\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062a}} meaning \"lady's wristlet\")\n|A disc-shaped pastry steeped in a honey syrup called \"''<nowiki>'</nowiki>atr''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0637\u0631}}) while the centre is covered with smashed [[pistachio]]s.\n|-\n|''[[Jalebi|Zilabiyyeh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0632\u0644\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|Thin sheets of semolina dough, boiled, rolled and stuffed with pistachios or milk cream called \"''qishteh''\" ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0634\u0637\u0629}}).\n|-\n|''Ghazal al-banat'' ({{lang|ar|\u063a\u0632\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u062a}})\n|Sugar cotton candy stuffed with pistachios or [[cashew]].\n|-\n|''Halaweh Homsiyyeh'' ({{lang|ar|\u062d\u0644\u0627\u0648\u0629 \u062d\u0645\u0635\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|\n|-\n|''Znud as-sitt'' ({{lang|ar|\u0632\u0646\u0648\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062a}} meaning \"lady's arms\")\n|[[Phyllo]] pastries with various fillings.\n|}\n\n== Cakes ==\n* [[Nygella Cake]]\n\n==Cheeses==\n{{main|List of Syrian Cheeses}}\n*[[Tresse cheese]] (Jibne Khadra) is a form of string cheese, that originates in Syria, known by its Arabic name '' Jibneh Mshallaleh ''.\n*[[List of Syrian Cheeses#Jibne Baida|White cheese]], a white hard cheese with a pronounced salty taste\n*[[Shanklish]], cow's milk or sheep's milk cheeses\n*[[Halloumi cheese]], a semi-hard, unripened, brined cheese\n\n==Beverages==\n[[File:Arak Al Hayat from Syria.jpg|thumb|Special edition of 5 year-aged Arak al-Hayat (''<nowiki>'</nowiki>ara<nowiki>'</nowiki>'') from [[Homs]], [[Syria]].]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Description\n|-\n|''[[Arak (distilled beverage)|'Ara']]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0639\u0631\u0642}})\n|A distilled alcoholic spirit, transparent in color, made from [[anise]] seeds.\n|-\n|[[Wine]] ({{lang|ar|\u0646\u0628\u064a\u0630}})\n|An alcoholic beverage made from fermented grapes.\n|-\n|[[Beer in Syria|Syrian beer]] ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0628\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0651\u0629}})\n|A beverage prepared from yeast-fermented malt, flavored with [[hops]].\n|-\n|[[Syrian coffee]] ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629}})\n|A beverage made from lightly roasted [[coffee beans]] along with cardamom, and served in small cups (same as the Turkish coffee).\n|-\n|''[[Qamar al-Din]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0645\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646}})\n|A thick apricot juice, typically served for [[Iftar]] during [[Ramadan]].\n|-\n|''[[Mate (beverage)|Al-mateh]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u0647}})\n|A [[caffeine]]-infused drink produced from ground [[yerba mate]] leaves and served hot.\n|-\n|''[[Salep]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0633\u062d\u0644\u0628}})\n|A traditional winter beverage which is a flour made from the tubers of the orchid genus Orchis. Salep flour is consumed in beverages and desserts.\n|-\n|''[[Ayran|'Ayran]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0639\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646}})\n|A yogurt-based beverage mixed with salt and water.\n|-\n|''[[Polo (beverage)|Polo]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u0628\u0648\u0644\u0648}})\n|Mint lemonade.\n|-\n|''[[Jallab]]'' ({{lang|ar|\u062c\u0644\u0627\u0628}})\n|A [[fruit syrup]] which can be combined with liquid to form a hot or warm beverage.\n|-\n|''Qahweh bayda<noinclude>'</noinclude>'' ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629 \u0628\u064a\u0636\u0627\u0621}} meaning \"white coffee\")\n|A caffeine-free drink made from water and orange blossom water, sweetened with sugar at will, usually served in lieu of coffee.\n\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[Mediterranean cuisine]]\n* [[Levantine cuisine]]\n* [[Middle Eastern cuisine]]\n* [[Arab cuisine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* Syrian wine [[Ch\u00e2teau Bargylus]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Gerbino|first=Virginia Jerro|title=A taste of Syria|date=2002|publisher=Hippocrene|location=New York|isbn=9780781809467|author2=Kayal, Philip }}\n* {{cite book|last=Kad\u00e9-Badra|first=Dalal|title=Flavours of Aleppo : celebrating Syrian cuisine|date=2013|publisher=Whitecap Books|location=Vancouver, Canada|isbn=9781770501782|author2=Badra, Elie }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline|Cuisine of Syria}}\n{{Mediterranean cuisine}}\n{{Middle East topic |prefix=Cuisine of |title=[[Middle Eastern cuisine]]}}\n{{Asian topic|| cuisine}}\n{{cuisine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Arab cuisine|Syria]]\n[[Category:Levantine cuisine|Syria]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean cuisine|Syria]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern cuisine|Syria]]\n[[Category:Syrian cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "GreenestMen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eadded lahmacun", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syrian_cuisine"}
{"title_page": "The Future (Steven Universe Future)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = The Future\n| series         = [[Steven Universe Future]]\n| image          = The_Future_000.png\n| caption        = Title card.\n| episode        = 20\n| director       = ''Supervising:'' Kat Morris<br>Alonso Ramirez Ramos<br>''Art:'' Liz Artinian\n| writer         = Lamar Abrams<br>Miki Brewster\n| editor         = \n| airdate        = March 27, 2020\n| prev           = [[Steven Universe Future#\"I Am My Monster\"|I Am My Monster]]\n| season_article = ''[[Steven Universe Future]]''\n| episode_list   = [[List of Steven Universe episodes#Steven Universe Future (2019-20)|List of Steven Universe episodes]]\n}}\n\n'''\"The Future\"''' is the 20th and final episode of the American [[animated]] [[limited series (television)|limited series]] ''[[Steven Universe Future]]'', which serves as an epilogue to the 2013-19 television series ''[[Steven Universe]]''; it is therefore also the final episode of the ''[[Steven Universe]]'' franchise. It originally aired on [[Cartoon Network]] on March 27, 2020 as the fourth and final part of the [[series finale]].<ref name=\"LosAngelesTimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/tv/story/2020-02-20/steven-universe-future-series-finale|title=The end of a world: 'Steven Universe' finale coming soon on Cartoon Network|date=February 20, 2020|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis final episode takes place in the aftermath of the events of the series, which focuses on protagonist [[Steven Universe (character)|Steven Universe]]'s unresolved trauma and need to feel needed by his friends and family. In the penultimate episode, Steven's stress builds up to the point that he becomes a monster and attacks his hometown of Beach City, until the unconditional emotional support of his loved ones brings him back to normal. In the finale, Steven finally decides to leave Beach City, but he worries that [[Garnet (Steven Universe)|Garnet]], [[Amethyst (Steven Universe)|Amethyst]], and [[Pearl (Steven Universe)|Pearl]] won't miss him after his departure.\n\n== Plot ==\nSteven discusses with his friend Connie his plan to leave Beach City and travel the country; he has told everyone about his decision except the Gems. He worries that they will be upset and hopes he can let them down easy.\n\nLater that day, Steven shares homemade Cookie Cat ice cream sandwiches with Garnet, Amethyst, and Pearl. The Gems sing the Cookie Cat advertising jingle, according to which Cookie Cat \"left his family behind\". Steven uses that to segue into his announcement that he's decided to move out the next day. He urges the Gems not to talk him out of his decision; but they seem to take his decision very lightly and are proud of him showing a desire to be independent. \u00a0\n\nBismuth, Lapis, and Peridot burst into tears when he gives them the news. Steven gives them farewell gifts: his old pink shirt for Peridot, a drawing and painting kit for Lapis, and the Crystal Gems' old battle flag for Bismuth.\n\nJasper insists on coming with him to protect him, but he assures her that he can protect himself.\n\nBack at the Temple, Steven gives Amethyst, Pearl, and Garnet their farewell gifts: Amethyst gets his old video games, Pearl his ukulele, and Garnet the wedding plan book he used to plan Ruby and Sapphire's wedding. All three accept the gifts nonchalantly, showing little concern about Steven's impending departure. Steven's father Greg tells him they are probably just trying to be supportive. As his parting gift for Greg, Steven encourages his father to move into Steven's room in the beach house.\n\nSteven says his goodbyes and drives off toward his next destination, but soon stops the car and returns to confront the Gems, demanding to know why they are taking the situation so lightly. The Gems burst into tears and explain that they didn't want their sad thoughts to prevent Steven from leaving. They assure him that, whatever happens in his future, they'll be part of it too. Everyone says they love each other, they give Steven one more goodbye, and he leaves his old home to a new path in his future. The people of Beach City wave goodbye as Steven begins his road trip, ending the episode, the series, and the ''Steven Universe'' franchise.\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Viewership ===\nThe episode was watched by 0.74 million people.<ref name=\"FinalEpisodes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-friday-cable-originals-network-finals-3-27-2020.html|title=Top 150 Friday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 3.27.2020|work=Showbuzz Daily|author=Mitch Metcalf|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Future ==\nWhile Rebecca Sugar has confirmed that this is the series finale and that there is no continuation in development, nor any ongoing projects, she has hinted that possible future stories exist. \"The story is continuing off screen and I do know what happens next...But I would have to decide how and when I'd want to dig into that, or if it's best to give them their privacy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/27/21197679/steven-universe-future-ending-finale-new-seasons-rebecca-sugar-interview|title=The reason Rebecca Sugar made Steven Universe Future, and why it\u2019s the actual end|last=Robinson|first=Tasha|date=March 27, 2020|website=Polygon|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSugar later told ''[[Fast Company]]'' \"I'm certainly interested in spending more time in this world with these characters. But the thing about ''Steven Universe'', it's about Steven Universe and I want to give him the time to heal\", [Sugar says.] \"I want to give that to my team as well. So I'm not really sure for certain what's going to happen in the future. I have a few ideas, but I'm going to take a little time to reevaluate everything before I jump into them.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90480992/steven-universe-creator-rebecca-sugar-explains-the-series-finale-future-and-her-future|title=\u2018Steven Universe\u2019 creator Rebecca Sugar explains the series finale, \u2018Future\u2019\u2014and her future|last=Ifeanyi|first=K. C.|date=2020-03-31|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{Steven Universe}}\n\n[[Category:Steven Universe episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = The Future\n| series         = [[Steven Universe Future]]\n| image          = The_Future_000.png\n| caption        = Title card.\n| episode        = 20\n| director       = ''Supervising:'' Kat Morris<br>Alonso Ramirez Ramos<br>''Art:'' Liz Artinian\n| writer         = Lamar Abrams<br>Miki Brewster\n| editor         = \n| airdate        = March 27, 2020\n| prev           = [[Steven Universe Future#\"I Am My Monster\"|I Am My Monster]]\n| season_article = ''[[Steven Universe Future]]''\n| episode_list   = [[List of Steven Universe episodes#Steven Universe Future (2019-20)|List of Steven Universe episodes]]\n}}\n\n'''\"The Future\"''' is the 20th and final episode of the American [[animated]] [[limited series]] ''[[Steven Universe Future]]'', which serves as an epilogue to the 2013-19 television series ''[[Steven Universe]]''; it is therefore also the final episode of the ''[[Steven Universe]]'' franchise. It originally aired on [[Cartoon Network]] on March 27, 2020 as the fourth and final part of the [[series finale]].<ref name=\"LosAngelesTimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/tv/story/2020-02-20/steven-universe-future-series-finale|title=The end of a world: 'Steven Universe' finale coming soon on Cartoon Network|date=February 20, 2020|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis final episode takes place in the aftermath of the events of the series, which focuses on protagonist [[Steven Universe (character)|Steven Universe]]'s unresolved trauma and need to feel needed by his friends and family. In the penultimate episode, Steven's stress builds up to the point that he becomes a monster and attacks his hometown of Beach City, until the unconditional emotional support of his loved ones brings him back to normal. In the finale, Steven finally decides to leave Beach City, but he worries that [[Garnet (Steven Universe)|Garnet]], [[Amethyst (Steven Universe)|Amethyst]], and [[Pearl (Steven Universe)|Pearl]] won't miss him after his departure.\n\n== Plot ==\nSteven discusses with his friend Connie his plan to leave Beach City and travel the country; he has told everyone about his decision except the Gems. He worries that they will be upset and hopes he can let them down easy.\n\nLater that day, Steven shares homemade Cookie Cat ice cream sandwiches with Garnet, Amethyst, and Pearl. The Gems sing the Cookie Cat advertising jingle, according to which Cookie Cat \"left his family behind\". Steven uses that to segue into his announcement that he's decided to move out the next day. He urges the Gems not to talk him out of his decision; but they seem to take his decision very lightly and are proud of him showing a desire to be independent. \u00a0\n\nBismuth, Lapis, and Peridot burst into tears when he gives them the news. Steven gives them farewell gifts: his old pink shirt for Peridot, a drawing and painting kit for Lapis, and the Crystal Gems' old battle flag for Bismuth.\n\nJasper insists on coming with him to protect him, but he assures her that he can protect himself.\n\nBack at the Temple, Steven gives Amethyst, Pearl, and Garnet their farewell gifts: Amethyst gets his old video games, Pearl his ukulele, and Garnet the wedding plan book he used to plan Ruby and Sapphire's wedding. All three accept the gifts nonchalantly, showing little concern about Steven's impending departure. Steven's father Greg tells him they are probably just trying to be supportive. As his parting gift for Greg, Steven encourages his father to move into Steven's room in the beach house.\n\nSteven says his goodbyes and drives off toward his next destination, but soon stops the car and returns to confront the Gems, demanding to know why they are taking the situation so lightly. The Gems burst into tears and explain that they didn't want their sad thoughts to prevent Steven from leaving. They assure him that, whatever happens in his future, they'll be part of it too. Everyone says they love each other, they give Steven one more goodbye, and he leaves his old home to a new path in his future. The people of Beach City wave goodbye as Steven begins his road trip, ending the episode, the series, and the ''Steven Universe'' franchise.\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Viewership ===\nThe episode was watched by 0.74 million people.<ref name=\"FinalEpisodes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-friday-cable-originals-network-finals-3-27-2020.html|title=Top 150 Friday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 3.27.2020|work=Showbuzz Daily|author=Mitch Metcalf|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Future ==\nWhile Rebecca Sugar has confirmed that this is the series finale and that there is no continuation in development, nor any ongoing projects, she has hinted that possible future stories exist. \"The story is continuing off screen and I do know what happens next...But I would have to decide how and when I'd want to dig into that, or if it's best to give them their privacy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/27/21197679/steven-universe-future-ending-finale-new-seasons-rebecca-sugar-interview|title=The reason Rebecca Sugar made Steven Universe Future, and why it\u2019s the actual end|last=Robinson|first=Tasha|date=March 27, 2020|website=Polygon|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSugar later told ''[[Fast Company]]'' \"I'm certainly interested in spending more time in this world with these characters. But the thing about ''Steven Universe'', it's about Steven Universe and I want to give him the time to heal\", [Sugar says.] \"I want to give that to my team as well. So I'm not really sure for certain what's going to happen in the future. I have a few ideas, but I'm going to take a little time to reevaluate everything before I jump into them.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90480992/steven-universe-creator-rebecca-sugar-explains-the-series-finale-future-and-her-future|title=\u2018Steven Universe\u2019 creator Rebecca Sugar explains the series finale, \u2018Future\u2019\u2014and her future|last=Ifeanyi|first=K. C.|date=2020-03-31|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{Steven Universe}}\n\n[[Category:Steven Universe episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Ajd", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix link target", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Future_(Steven_Universe_Future)"}
{"title_page": "Bailee Madison", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bailee Madison\n| image              = Bailee Madison 2015 TV Critics Association Tour (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Madison in January 2015\n| birth_name         = <!--- Only include if different from article name --->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1999|10|15|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| relatives          = [[Kaitlin Vilasuso]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Bailee Madison''' (born October 15, 1999)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.no/detail/news-photo/bailee-madison-celebrates-her-13th-birthday-on-october-20-news-photo/154489850|title=Bailee Madison celebrates her 13th birthday on October 20, 2012 in...|website=Getty Images}}</ref> is an American actress. She first gained acclaim for her role as [[May Belle Aarons]] in the fantasy drama film ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]'' (2007). Madison received further recognition for her starring roles as Isabelle in the war drama film ''[[Brothers (2009 film)|Brothers]]'' (2009), Sally Hurst in the horror film ''[[Don't Be Afraid of the Dark (2010 film)|Don't Be Afraid of the Dark]]'' (2010), Maggie in the romantic comedy film ''[[Just Go with It]]'' (2011), Harper Simmons in the comedy film ''[[Parental Guidance (film)|Parental Guidance]]'' (2012), Clementine in the fantasy film ''[[Northpole (film)|Northpole]]'' (2014), and Kinsey in the slasher horror film ''[[The Strangers: Prey at Night]]'' (2018).\n\nOn television, she appeared as [[Maxine Russo]] in the fantasy sitcom ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]'' (2011), young [[Snow White]] in the fantasy drama series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]'' (2012\u201316), Hillary Harrison in the sitcom ''[[Trophy Wife (TV series)|Trophy Wife]]'' (2013\u201314), and Sophia Quinn in the drama series ''[[The Fosters (2013 TV series)|The Fosters]]'' (2014\u201316). From 2015 to 2019, Madison starred as Grace Russell in the [[Hallmark Channel]] comedy-drama series ''[[Good Witch (TV series)|Good Witch]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nMadison was born in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]],<ref name=\"issue\">{{Cite magazine | title = Bailee Madison | url = https://issuemagazine.com/bailee_madison/ | magazine = Issue Magazine | access-date = October 10, 2019 |quote=Where are you from? I was born in Fort Lauderdale, Florida! I grew up in a town called Lauderdale by the Sea, and I still go home whenever I can.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fortlauderdaledaily.com/features/fort-lauderdale-native-and-actress-bailee-madison-talks-us-about-growing-south-florida-her|title=Bailee Madison Talks To Us About Growing Up In South Florida, Her Career And More|website=Fort Lauderdale Daily|language=en|access-date=August 20, 2019}}</ref> the youngest of seven children. She has four brothers and two sisters. Her older sister, [[Kaitlin Riley]], is also an actress. Her mother is Patricia Riley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.childreninfilm.com/Fame-Success-Stories-Bailee.aspx |title=Children in Film |publisher=|date= |accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref> She began her career when she was two weeks old, appearing in an [[Office Depot]] commercial. Since then, she has appeared in several national commercials for major companies including [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]], [[SeaWorld]], and [[Cadillac]]. She also serves as a national youth spokesperson for the childhood-cancer charity [[Alex's Lemonade Stand|Alex's Lemonade Stand Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelguidemagblog.com/index.php/2011/12/09/bailee-madison-returns-to-the-hubs-haunting-hour-with-scarecrow/|author=Stacey Harrison|title=Bailee Madison returns to The Hub's \"Haunting Hour\" with \"Scarecrow\"|work=channelguidemag.com|accessdate=December 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z-o7nu1fTi0|author=I Am Second|title=I Am Second Bailee Madison \u2013 Child Actress|work=youtube.com|accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2006\u20132012: Early career and breakthrough===\nMadison made her major motion picture debut in the movie ''[[Lonely Hearts (2006 film)|Lonely Hearts]]'', in which she plays Rainelle, a girl thrown into the midst of a world of crime. Madison also has a significant role in the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] movie ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]'', based on the children's book. She plays May Belle Aarons, the younger sister of the lead male character played by [[Josh Hutcherson]]. She also appears in the [[independent film]] ''[[Look (2007 film)|Look]]'' as Megan, a girl who is being watched and followed by a kidnapper.\n[[File:Bailee Madison.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Madison at the Faith and Values Awards Gala in 2008]]\n\nMadison had a small role in ''[[Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles]]'' during the season 1 finale \"What He Beheld\" as a girl who becomes part of a short-lived hostage situation. In the DVD extras it is said that they thought about changing the role slightly because of its violent nature, but she insisted that they not. Madison appeared in [[Nickelodeon]]'s made-for-TV movie, ''[[The Last Day of Summer (2007 film)|The Last Day of Summer]]''. She plays a girl who helps a friend during a difficult time. Another Nickelodeon production she had a role in was the television Christmas special ''[[Merry Christmas, Drake & Josh]]''. She played a girl who lived with a foster family.\n\nMadison is seen in a featured supporting role in the 2009 film ''[[Brothers (2009 film)|Brothers]]'' as Isabelle Cahill, the older daughter of Captain Sam Cahill ([[Tobey Maguire]]) and Grace Cahill ([[Natalie Portman]]). For her portrayal in the movie, she was nominated for both a [[Saturn Award]] and a [[BFCA|BFCA Critics' Choice Award]]. In 2010, Madison was in the movie ''[[Letters to God]]'', where she portrayed Samantha Perryfield, best friend of the lead character who is fighting cancer.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nShe is seen in ''[[Conviction (2010 film)|Conviction]]'' playing the younger version of [[Hilary Swank|Hilary Swank's]] character, Betty Anne Waters. She can be seen in the episode \"Locum\" from ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' as Mackenzie Burton, a girl who was adopted and feels like she is only filling the place of her parents' older daughter who was abducted years ago. She appeared in three episodes of the children's horror series, ''[[R.L. Stine's The Haunting Hour]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn 2011, Madison had a recurring role in the [[Disney Channel]] [[List of Disney Channel series|Original Series]] ''[[Wizards of Waverly Place]]'' as Maxine, the girl form of [[Max Russo]]. She also appeared in ''[[Just Go with It]]'', alongside [[Adam Sandler]] and [[Jennifer Aniston]], as Maggie Murphy, a young girl who wants to become an actress. Madison can be seen in the drama film, ''[[An Invisible Sign]]'' as the younger version of [[Jessica Alba|Jessica Alba's]] character Mona Gray. She starred in her first leading role in the [[horror film]], ''[[Don't Be Afraid of the Dark (2011 film)|Don't Be Afraid of the Dark]]'', alongside [[Katie Holmes]] and [[Guy Pearce]] where she portrayed Sally Hurst, a lonely withdrawn child who is sent to live with her father and his new girlfriend.\n\nIn 2012, Madison appeared in the [[Hallmark]] film ''A Taste of Romance'' alongside [[Teri Polo]] and [[James Patrick Stuart]]. She also had a guest role as the younger version of [[Ginnifer Goodwin]]'s character [[Snow White]] in the TV series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''. She also could be seen as the main character in the film ''[[Cowgirls n' Angels]]'' where she played the feisty and rebellious Ida Clayton who has fantasies of finding her father, a rodeo rider. Madison appeared in another Hallmark film entitled ''Smart Cookie'' as Daisy, an eager girl hoping to prove herself as a Girl Scout. In December, she appeared in the family comedy film ''[[Parental Guidance (film)|Parental Guidance]]'', alongside [[Billy Crystal]] and [[Bette Midler]].\n\n===2013\u2013present: Continued success===\n[[File:Bailee Madison 2012.jpg|thumb|upright|Madison at the Golden Globes Gift Lounge on January 14, 2012]]\nIn 2013, Madison began playing Hillary on the TV sitcom ''[[Trophy Wife (TV series)|Trophy Wife]]'', replacing Gianna LePera who played the character in the pilot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bailee Madison Trophy Wife|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/09/09/trophy-wife-pilot-review|publisher=IGN|accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, she began playing the recurring role of Sophia Quinn in the [[ABC Family]] drama ''[[The Fosters (2013 TV series)|The Fosters]]''. In 2015, she began playing Grace Russell, the daughter of Cassie Nightingale, in the Hallmark series ''[[Good Witch (TV series)|Good Witch]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018Good Witch\u2019 Star Bailee Madison Teases Spellbinding Season 2|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/good-witch-star-bailee-madison-teases-season-2-drama-mysterious-newcomers-her-2354624|website=International Business Times|accessdate=October 8, 2016|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref> Madison continued in the role until the end of the fifth season in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2019/07/03/good-witch-bailee-madison-leaving-grace-season-6/|title=Good Witch Twist: Bailee Madison Exits Ahead of Just-Ordered Season 6|first1=Michael|last1=Ausiello|first2=Michael|last2=Ausiello|date=July 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, it was announced that Madison would star in an adaptation of Rachel Bateman's novel ''[[Someone Else's Summer]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Bailee Madison to Star in \u2018Someone Else\u2019s Summer\u2019 Movie Adaptation (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/bailee-madison-someone-elses-summer-movie-1202410698/|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Madison portrayed the role of Kinsey, a rebellious child in slasher horror film ''[[The Strangers: Prey at Night]].'' She starred alongside [[Christina Hendricks]] and [[Martin Henderson]], as her parents. The film received a mixed response from critics and was relatively successful at the box office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2018/03/09/strangers-prey-night-review/|title=Review \u2013 Strangers: Prey at Night is Why Some Films Don't Need Sequels|date=March 9, 2018|work=Bleeding Cool News And Rumors|access-date=March 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/03/film-review-the-strangers-prey-at-night-is-a-quick-bloody-slasher-throwback/|title=Film Review: The Strangers: Prey at Night is a Quick, Bloody Slasher Throwback|date=March 8, 2018|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=March 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nMadison has worked in [[voice-over|voice over]], with such projects as ''Breathe Bible''.<ref>[http://breathebible.com/voices/bailee-madison \"Bailee Madison, The Voice of Young Mary\"], BreatheBible.com; retrieved September 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nMadison has served as the national youth spokesperson for [[Alex's Lemonade Stand Foundation]] since 2010, an organization that encourages kids to fundraise and spread awareness of pediatric cancer by running their own lemonade stands.<ref name=\"foxnews\">[http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/06/12/young-actress-bailee-madison-sells-lemonade-for-charity-celebrates-girl-scouts \"Young actress Bailee Madison sells lemonade for charity, celebrates Girl Scouts 100th anniversary with new role\"], FoxNews.com, June 12, 2012.</ref> In January 2018, Madison's first novel was published, ''Losing Brave'', a [[Young adult fiction|Young-Adult]] Mystery which was co-written with Stefne Miller.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/34460488-losing-brave|title=Losing Brave|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> Since November 2018, she has co-hosted the podcast ''Just Between Us'' with her sister [[Kaitlin Vilasuso]].<ref>{{cite web |title=PodcastOne: Just Between Us with Bailee Madison & Kaitlin Vilasuso |url=https://www.podcastone.com/just-between-us |publisher=[[PodcastOne]] |accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe dated YouTuber and model Alex Lange from September 2016 to December 2018.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-ug0KhxViGs</ref> Neither Lange nor Madison spoke about the break up, but AwesomenessTV put out a YouTube video to announce this.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ZFczmN0_To</ref>\n\nSince around April 2019, she has been in a relationship with New Hope Club band member and lead singer Blake Richardson.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B01LiqhnA3J/</ref> It is uncertain when exactly they started dating, however several Instagram posts from both, (the earliest ones in May<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/Bx7ZLI_jlbC/</ref> and June<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/ByS9KbGHRtg/</ref>) and the YouTube video on New Hope Club's channel filmed in April hints at their relationship.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D6hnqut2_VY</ref>\n\nMadison posts frequently about him on her Instagram stories, Twitter and main Instagram feed, generally in support of his work but also sharing sweet moments with him.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/baileemadison/</ref> <ref>https://twitter.com/BaileeMadison</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Lonely Hearts (2006 film)|Lonely Hearts]]'' || Rainelle Downing ||\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disney.go.com/disneyvideos/liveaction/bridgetoterabithia/ |title=Bridge to Terabithia official site 